<br>
The first one I actually hacked and figured out the internals of (by stopping it with the ROM debugger and reverse-engineering the data structures using MacsBug - bwahahaha) was Strategic Conquest, also on Macs of about the same era. The risk versus reward was quite appropriate, since if you slightly messed up the new data you wrote into system RAM, the uber destroyer you just created was on the enemy team, and would run wild, creating a situation from which it was very hard to recover.<br>
<br>
The first game I played that had halfway decent AI was Risk (the computer version of the board game), also on the Mac (starting to see a pattern here, aren't we?). My friends and I still play the colorized version of this regularly, fifteen years after we discovered it - that says a heck of a lot. I actually have a halfway-decent Mac emulator for my PC (Basilisk II) solely to play this game.<br>
<br>
Another one of my big favorites from a slightly later time frame (1990 or so) was Harpoon, a Cold War-era naval warfare simulation. With the scenario editor you could devise some awesome tricks to play on your friends. If they had only released a true multi-player version, this game would have kicked some serious booty - actually, it did anyway. That's another one that we still play on occasion. There were sequels to Harpoon but, sadly, they all sucked. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ucerosofvazaelle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ceros of Vazaelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1008<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/8/02 5:06:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3342.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> .</span><hr size=1> I'm going to stick with PC games and leave out my console/arcade favorites.<br>
